I've just run through a quick vibe coding project. I plan to update the general project here.

First, I asked a web based AI tool for some ideas on platform engineering, y'know, "like backstage" but with the constraints that 
they be ideas that are do-able in a day. 

So from there I had a list of a half dozen platform engineering-ish ideas. I then took the first idea and told it to change the destination
targets from AWS or a K8s cluster to a local emulator like moto or minikube or docker, etc. 

Then I asked for a directory structure (this web AI agent had a tendency to spoon feed me elements and give me files but not say where they go, so the directory
was pretty useful in seeing how much wasn't done and where. 

I deliberately chose a web UI AI agent with a copy and paste style system because this made me a "Man in the Middle": 
I could see what was being done, how it was being done. I was being forced into the guts of the process rather than
just running a cli in -yolo mode that could whip something out. And it tended to produce code that didn't work, so 
troubleshooting was almost always a part of the process. 

I feel troubleshooting is important: working through errors, fixing paths, seeing what happens when things don't work.

A broken script is more instructional that a working one, and this AI agent produced lots of very instructional broken
code. 

I got to grapple with an github action for this, which was new to me although I'd worked extensively with jenkins and gitlab's pipeline feature. 
So conceptually it wasn't new. 

The goal was something that could be done in a day and it took about that.  The first round was 100% AI code with lots of
errors. The iterations were human in the middle AI + human errors. And the result is all "vibes". 
